            <ObservedData>
              <Attribute Type="Description">Stasia et al. (2002) used RT-PCR amplification and sequencing to demonstrate a mutation in the p22-PHOX mRNA in a patient with autosomal recessive cytochrome b-negative CGD (CGD4; 233690). The defect was a 179-bp insertion associated with a 21-bp deletion of the beginning of exon 5 at position 315 from the translation start codon of the cDNA. This defect was also detected in the patient's parents. In the genomic DNA of the patient, the molecular defect was a homozygous 36-bp deletion in the linking sequence between intron 4 and exon 5. This genomic deletion corresponded to 15 bp of the 3-prime extremity of intron 4 and 21 bp of the beginning of exon 5 (the same deletion of exon 5 seen in the corresponding mRNA). The splicing mRNA error was attributable to the loss of the AG acceptor site of intron 4 and the utilization of a cryptic splice site with an AG sequence at position 355-356 of intron 4.</Attribute>
